\begin{cases}
x - 3y + 3z = 8 \\
2x - 6y + 6z = 2
\end{cases}
\]
This simplifies to \[
\begin{cases}
x - 3y + 3z = 8 \\
x - 3y + 3z = 1
\end{cases}
\]
We can subtract the second equation from the first to get a system with a simpler form. The next step is to recognize that the distance between two parallel planes \(ax + by + cz = d_1\) and \(ax + by + cz = d_2\) is given by \[
\text{Distance} = \frac{|d_1 - d_2|}{\sqrt{a^2 + b^2 + c^2}}
\]
Here, the planes can be written as \(x - 3y + 3z = 8\) and \(x - 3y + 3z = 1\). The distance is \[
\text{Distance} = \frac{|8 - 1|}{\sqrt{1^2 + (-3)^2 + 3^2}} = \frac{7}{\sqrt{1 + 9 + 9}} = \frac{7}{\sqrt{19}}
\]
We can rationalize this to get the final answer. \[
\text{Distance} = \frac{7\sqrt{19}}{19}
\]
